Unit Testing Guidelines

For the web & API project — please read before pushing anything.


--Naming Convention

Test methods should follow this pattern:

MethodName_StateUnderTest_ExpectedBehavior

Examples:
GetUser_InvalidId_ReturnsNotFound
CreateOrder_EmptyCart_ThrowsException
CalculateTotal_WithDiscount_ReturnsCorrectAmount

Test classes should be named after the class they test, with a "Tests" suffix:
UserServiceTests
OrderControllerTests


--Coverage Requirements

Minimum 80% code coverage per class you write.
Every public method needs at least one test.
Make sure you cover the happy path (normal expected behavior), edge cases (null inputs, empty lists, boundary values), and error/exception cases.



--Before You Push

Do not push if your tests are failing. Period.

Before every push make sure: all tests pass locally with dotnet test, no tests are skipped without a reason, new code has corresponding tests, and coverage is at or above 80%.

If something is broken and you're stuck, open an issue or ask. Do not just comment out the test.


--General Notes

Keep tests independent, one test should not rely on another.
Do not put business logic inside tests, keep them simple and readable.
